	abstract = {Created wetlands play an important role in the conservation of Least{\textbackslash}{nBitterns} (Ixobrychus exilis) by compensating for the loss of natural{\textbackslash}nwetlands. In 2011, we studied habitat relationships of a major{\textbackslash}npopulation breeding in a 128-ha cattail- and bur-reed-dominated{\textbackslash}nimpoundment in Quebec. We surveyed for bitterns and recorded habitat{\textbackslash}nparameters at 30 points, making novel use of a small unmanned aircraft{\textbackslash}nsystem ({UAS}) to obtain fine-scale land cover data. A model-selection{\textbackslash}napproach based on Akaike's information criterion ({AIC}) determined that{\textbackslash}nbreeding density was best predicted by cattail cover in combination with{\textbackslash}nwater-vegetation edge density (Akaike weight = 0.88). Breeding density{\textbackslash}nwas unrelated to water depth, contrary to a previous study at the site{\textbackslash}nafter a dyke breach significantly lowered water levels, suggesting that{\textbackslash}nabove a certain depth threshold other habitat preferences take{\textbackslash}nprecedence. We recommend that management of created wetlands for Least{\textbackslash}{nBitterns} focus on maintaining stable water levels of at least 25 cm on{\textbackslash}naverage during the breeding season and manipulating them as required{\textbackslash}nlater on in order to promote hemi-marsh conditions. {UAS} can enhance{\textbackslash}nwetland habitat research and monitoring by improving the precision and{\textbackslash}nefficiency of data collection in the field while reducing disturbance{\textbackslash}ncompared to ground-based surveys.},
